\begin_layout Title
Past and future in Black Holes
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Part three of the Ergodicity/Entropy series
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
31 May 2023
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This text proposes a series of thought experiments involving 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

physical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 objects falling through the event horizon of a Schwarschild black hole.
 The first is that of a free-falling observer, with a free-falling flashlight
 in front.
 What does the observer see, as the flashlight crosses the event horizon?
 This thought experiment can be generalized in various ways, including (for
 example) a free-falling machine gun shooting BB's at a fixed energy and
 regular rate.
 All of these should be exactly, precisely solvable, as the Schwarschild
 metric seems easy enough to do so.
 A second set of thought experiments are proposed, involving the Huygens
 sum of the quantities from the first.
 It is hypothesized that the Huygens sum should correspond to the classical
 wave wquations in curved spacetime (but I have not yet done the calculations,
 so I don't know.) It is possible that there is some textbook or ArXiv preprint
 that already solves all of this, but I don't know.
 Onward ho!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction: Past and future
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here's a confusing thought experiment.
 Suppose one follows a free-falling (non-spinning) geodesic into a Schwarschild
 black hole.
 This is radial motion.
 Suppose that, in front of you, there is a free-falling flashlight, aimed
 back at you.
 That is, the flashlight is always closer to the event horizon than you
 are.
 What, exactly, happens, as you cross the event horizon?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the conventional interpretation, the flashlight grows dimmer
 and redshifts as it approaches the horizon, going black as it crosses.
 This is independent of the fact that you are also falling: if it did not
 grow black, then you would be in a position to relay any information back
 out to infinity.
 So, it goes dark, no matter that you are falling after it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happens after you cross the horizon? I'm slightly confused, but I think
 this is the correct interpretation: I think the answer is that it stays
 dark.
 That is, it has fallen into the future, and cannot affect you in any way.
 It would be nice to work this out in detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now a spherical shell of such lights: in front, to the sides, behind.
 Initialy, these are uniformly distributed and of equal brightness.
 As the observer in the center of this spherical shell, what do you see?
 Without yet having solved the eqns, I hypothesize this: you see the front
 of the shell redshift and grow dark, and then a growing ring at the edge
 to the same, so that a disk (of some angular size) in front of you is dark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conventional interpretation of redshift in flat space is that it arises
 from objects accelerating away from you.
 So, in this sense, increasingly large parts of the sphere have accelerated
 away from you.
 This creates a mild paradox with the conventional description of tidal
 forces, of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spaghettification
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which implies squeezing in the orthogonal direction, and stretching along
 the radial direction.
 So for example, the flashlights beside and behind you, are they red-shifted
 or blue-shifted?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thanks to the magic of GPS, we can time-stamp the flashlight emissions with
 the proper time for the emitter; so the receiver can always unambiguously
 know when a signal was emitted.
 Recall how this is done: each GPS transmitter (in this case, the LED of
 the flashlight) blinks out a pseudo-random sequence of bits.
 Based on the received bitstream, the receiver can know what the proper
 time was, when the stream was transmitted.
 This has the nice side-effect of not only talking about coordinate systems
 in the abstract, but allowing that information to be encoded in a concrete
 fashion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conventional narratives talk about brightness.
 and so we have to ask about that as well.
 What, exactly, do we mean by brightness? There are two aspects to tis question.
 First: are there areas where the flashlights appear to bunch up toghether
 (and thus get brighter?) Second: of the narrow cone of emitted light, coming
 from that flashlight, is most of that cone dispersed away from you (thus
 getting dimmer), or is it focused towards you (thus getting brighter?)
 This second question assumes that brightness corresponds to the density
 of incoming null geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above thought experiment was phrased with flashlights, so that we consider
 only those light-like geodesics that connect the flashlight, and you, the
 observer.
 There is now a secondary question: as this flashlights fall, do they continue
 to be aimed at the center of the sphere, or do they twist away in some
 other direction? If so, which direction? What is the formula for that?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happens if the flashlights are replaced by uniform emitters? This situation
 is rather more complicated, as, before the sphere of emitters crosses the
 even horizon, some of those null geodesics can orbit the black hole one
 or more times.
 What happens after all of the shell has fallen through the event horizon?
 Does one still see incoming null geodesics from outside, or do these all
 wink out, before one hits the singularity?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The orbiting geodesics problem is topologically interesting.
 It is a discretization: each orbit can be assigned an integer.
 In effect, this is a physical process by which a continuum is sliced up
 into discrete parts.
 The slicing of continua into pieces by differential equations is somewhat
 unusual and is interesting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above treated light as a scalar, without any polarization.
 All calculations have to be redone with the case of polarization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now repeat the exercise with massive particles.
 That is, replace the flashlight by a machine gun shooting BB's at you,
 fixing the mass of the BB, the rate of fire, and the momentum/energy of
 the shot.
 These are the time-like geodesics.
 What do you see? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, repeat the exercise with spinning bullets.
 The spin can be arbitrarily oriented.
 Is there precession?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, repeat this with Weyl spinors.
 These are massless, and follow null geodesics.
 This is somewhat confusing, since along each null geodesic, we have to
 provide a fierbein, so that we can construct the Clifford algebra in the
 fierbein coordinate system, and then construct the Weyl spinors in that
 coordinate system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And then, one more step: repeat this with classical Dirac point particles.
 So, just like above, we assign to heave timelike geodesic a fierbein, slap
 the Dirac gamma matrices onto it, and then discuss the time evolution of
 Dirac spinors, as they move along these freely-falling geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Huygens sums
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above was a program for determining the behavior of classical particles,
 moving along null or timelike geodesics.
 We now want to repeat the exercise, this time performing Huygens sums.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correct way to do this is to imagine falling with a massless dust of
 robots.
 The job of each robot is to intercept all particles propagating on all
 geodesics that intersect with the robot, perform a sum of all amplitudes
 and phases on those geodesics, and then to become a point emitter, and
 re-radiate that data, uniformly in all directions in that robots local
 free-falling coordinate frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the null geodesics, we need to track not only the frequency (redshift/bluesh
ift) but also a phase.
 The phase is presumably an integral over the proper time along the geodesic.
 This is fine for timelike geodesics, but what about null geodesics? Is
 the phase synchronous along the null geodesic? That is, can we take the
 phase to just be a constant number along the null geodesic? That is, each
 flashlight emits three things: a null geodesic, a complex number (the phase)
 that is held constant on the geodesic, and (optionally) a polarization
 vector that ...
 ?? Does the polarization evolve according to the connection between the
 frame fields, or is it held constant?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anyway, when this Huygens sum is performed, is the result the classical
 wave equation in curved spacetime?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the massive particles (time-like geodesics), the phase evolves as a
 clock moving in proper time.
 The Huygens sum will presumably result in the Klien–Gordon equation.
 But this is a hypothesis; it is not obvious that this will actually happen.
 How does all of this work out? What are the details?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the classical point-particle spinors, the Huygens sum presumably results
 in the Weyl wave equation in curved spacetime? Likewise for classical point-par
ticle Dirac spinors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Tropes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the common tropes is that of an astronaut who falls through the event
 horizon.
 The common saying, available in many textbooks, is that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nothing happens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the astronaut, as he falls through the even horizon.
 However, this cannot be true!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, for example, consider the astronaut diving, such that his hands are
 in front of him.
 Say, for example, that his space-suit glows, so that he can see his hands
 in front of him.
 What happens during those few moments when his hands are inside the event
 horizon, but his eyballs are still outside? Can he see his hands? I would
 think not! The light from his glowing gloves, inside the EH, cannot reach
 his eyeballs, which are still outside the EH.
 At best, he might see his gloves infinitely red-shifted as they approach
 the EH.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happens when his eyeballs pass the EH? Do his outstretched arms suddenly
 become visible again? I'm not sure, because I have not yet done the calculation
s, but I think the answer is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The photons do not arc back up the well, almost but not quite reaching
 the EH from the inside.
 The photons continue to fall, and the eyeballs never catch up to them,
 to detect them.
 The arms remain invisible.
 (They've 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fallen into the future.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several alternate visualizations one can imagine.
 Perhaps the astronaut has a cell phone in his hands, and that cell phone
 is performing some kind of calculations.
 If the astronaut was wearing a GoPro camera on his helmet, recording and
 retransmitting his descent across the EH, and if the GoPro could see the
 cell phone inside the EH, while still being outside of it, then this would
 be a way of transmitting info from inside the EH to the outside world.
 This is forbidden.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Mechanics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The considerations above wreck chemistry, as we know it, at least if chemsitry
 was a purely classical affair (and we know that it isn't.) But if it was:
 the atoms in the astronauts fingers, as they cross the event horizon, cannot
 propagate signals back up the arm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is, instead of atoms, imagine the astronaut was a robot, built from
 tiny gears: some kind of nanomechanical grey goo.
 The gears in the fingertips, after they've crossed the EH, can no longer
 transmit a signal up the arm, back to the head.
 For all intents and purposes, those gears have been disconnected from the
 arm.
 They disconnect as they cross the EH.
 Can they reconnect, after the rest of the arm has fallen through? I don't
 think so.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is this disconnection only an apparent phenomenon, and not a real one, because
 some kind of time-dilation argument for the gears? I don't think so, but
 I have not done the calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is still the possibility that the brain can send signals down through
 the arm, and, say, wiggle the fingers.
 In this sense, perhaps the gears remain 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

connected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 They just can't propagate a signal back.
 The nature of the (mechanical) connection is terribly weird, though.
 Effectively, the gears in the fingers are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in the future
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and can receive messages from the brain, because the brain is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in the past
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The brain cannot receive messages from the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this sense, we've demonstrated a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

firewall problem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, at least for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

machinery
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, some kind of abstract mechanical machinery not built from (quantum mechanical)
 atoms, but from some kind of incompressible material stuffs.
 The EH fundamentaly wrecks machinery.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The (classically-mechanical) astronaut does NOT fall through the EH 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unharmed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; he is fundamentally shredded by the rotation from space-like to time-like.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Quantum mechanics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above considerations are all derived by considering null geodesics as
 carriers of information.
 It ignores the quantum mechanical nature of atoms.
 So, for example, consider a strand of protein or DNA falling through the
 EH.
 A high-school explanation of chemistry is that molecules are held together
 by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

covalent bonds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which are electron clouds exchanging photons in some sort of magical,
 unexplained way with the nuclei that they are binding.
 This allows chemical bonds to vibrate, bend, stretch.
 What happens to those vibrational modes, as each amino acid of a long protein
 crosses the event horizon, bit by bit? Vibrations can travel one way down
 that chain, but not back the other way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In college chemistry, one is introduced to the Schrodinger equation, which
 is solved for the hydrogen atom.
 What holds the hydrogen atom together? The correct answer is either 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quantum mechanics does
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

do not ask that question
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The wrong answer is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a magic cloud of electrons and photons bouncing around in some ergodic fashion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This is wrong because the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

magic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and because 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ergodic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 implies local hidden variables, which are disallwed by Bell's theorem.
 The rest of chemistry marches onwards.
 For example: MO-LCAO (Molecular Orbitals are Linear Combinations of Atomic
 Orbitals) and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In college level expositions of quantum mechanics, the dynamical aspects
 are introduced by adding a phase 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{iEt}$
\end_inset

 for some time coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 By convention, time flows forward in time.
 The ket 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 propagates forward in time.
 The conjugate bra 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \psi\right|$
\end_inset

 propagates 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backwards in time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Effectively all of college-level QM is done with kets; the bras are only
 needed for operator matrix elements.
 There's no reason to dwell on the bras, because they are just the complex
 conjugates of the kets.
 Or so the students are lead to beleive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The finer points of weak measurements indicate that the two-vector state
 formalism (TVSF) is more appropriate, and that the calculations seem to
 be more correct and easier to interpret when one considers both the forward-tim
e propagating kets and the backwards-time propagating bras.
 Or at least, that is what some of the weak-measurements theory seems to
 lead to, when following one's nose.
 Of course, time symmetry is rampant by the time one gets to QFT, and we
 won't dwell on that, here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So now we get to the question: how does quantum chemistry work, as molecules
 fall through the event horizon? We've already indicated that the leading
 part of a protein falling through the EH is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in the future
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Is chemistry preserved, because we still have those bras, which are propagating
 effects from the future, back into the past? That, for example, the vibrating
 molecule that falls through the EH is undisturbed, because although the
 ket that's inside cannot propagate out of the EH, the bra can at least
 propagate 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backwards
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, right up to the EH? Something like that? Magic?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this time, my brain bonks here.
 I don't see how forward progress can be made, until the assorted geodesic
 problems posed above can be solved.
 I'm hoping that the Huygens summation can actually be performed, and that
 it yeilds some kind of insight beyond the plain old 
