\begin_layout Section
Plan of attack
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we need a suitable coordinate system for frames propagatinv along
 null geodesics.
 The Euler angles would be one, but that's cumbersome.
 Equivalently, one could work with Pauli matrices, and then compare to the
 Euler angles as needed.
 The Pauli matrices are just what the spin connection provides, and so we
 need to integrate the spin connection along null geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, for a scalar light field, we don't need to full set of Euler angles,
 so, for that case, we just need a way of parameterizing the null tangent
 space at some point in the Schwarschild space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Flashlight geodesics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The introduction proposes a priviledged point, the astronaut, surrounded
 by a spherical shell of infalling flashlights.
 For practical calculations, it is more convenient to visualize the astronaut
 as being surrounded by a cloud, a uniformly distributed dust of flashlights.
 The goal of this section is to describe the infalling geodesics of the
 astronaut and these flashlights.
 Since these are meant to be radially infalling, this should be easy.
 To make the notation unambiguous, some preliminaries need to be cleared
 up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Conceptual framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This dust of flashlights should be thought of as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smart dust
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, so that each flashlight is a computer, capable of carrying a universally
 unique id (UUID) that identifies it.
 When each flashlight broadcasts, it should be thought of as a GPS transmitter,
 so that the transmission encodes the UUID number.
 This does not alter the mathematical description of the geodesics in any
 way; instead, the goal here is that each geodesic can be given a unique,
 unambiguous label, about which there can be no confusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, when a flashlight broadcasts, it can also encode the direction
 in which it is broadcasting the signal.
 That is, each flashlight carries an intertial frame (say, by gyroscopes
 built into it), and when the flashlight transmits a narrow beam in some
 given direction, it can encode that direction into the beam itself.
 Recall the engineering of this: it can be done with pseudorandom bit sequences.
 The flashlight modulates the transmission with this directional information
 (using AM, FM, SSB, PCM, quadrature; any conventional radio technique will
 work.) Again, this changes nothing, other than reinforcing the idea that
 each null geodesic emanating from the flashlight can be uniquely identified
 with the initial direction in which it was emitted.
 The flashlight can also carry a clock, measuring the proper time for that
 flashlight, and this time can also be encoded into the transmission.
 Thus, for each null geodesic, it can be accurately labelled with a timestamp
 indicating the proper time when it was emitted.
 Note finally that each radio transmission can also be polarized, thus indicatin
g the remaining degree of freedom in the positioning of the transmitter.
 That is, radio waves can completely encode information about the transmitter
 at the time of the transmission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flashlight
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used, implying light or radio emissions propagating along null geodesics,
 these flashlights could equally be machine rifles, shooting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smart bullets
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In this case, each bullet could be a computer.
 This computer can carry information about which gun it was shot from, and
 when, and what direction (so, the same as the radio transmissions), but
 also the velocity.
 Each bullet can be equipped with a clock, and with gyroscopes, so that,
 again, there is no doubt whatsoever is to it's inertial frame.
 Each bullet is also capable of acting as a radio receiver, and recording
 a history of those receptions; bullets have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

memory of the past
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Upon reception of the bullet by the observer (the falling astronaut), this
 information can be queried and analyzed by the astronaut.
 Again, this does not change any of the algebra used to describe the geodesics;
 it does, however, sharpen the the kind of information that can be attached
 to the timelike geodesics emitted by the flashlight-guns.
 Also worth keeping in mind that the null geodesics cannot carry this kind
 of information.
 The null geodesic cannot 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

remember
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 what it saw along the way; the null geodesic has no proper time, no recording
 mechanism, no memory, no subjective, experienced history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Flashlight labels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now proceed to label the flashlights.
 Starting at a location 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg2m$
\end_inset

, where spacetime is approximately flat, we establish an inertial frame.
 This frame can be labelled with either orthonormal coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 or with polar coordinates.
 The labelling is done at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

, and we set the proper time to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 for all flashlights.
 There is no engineering or mathematical challenge to arranging this.
 Its all standard lab technique.
 Place the astronaut at the origin, the privileged point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y=z=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For polar coordinates, the following notation is used: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With respect to the Schwarschild coordinates, the astronaut is initially
 located at at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{0}\gg2m$
\end_inset

 and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 in the Schwarschild chart.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}}$
\end_inset

 be the radial location of a flashlight with respect to the astronaut.
 This number should be thought of as a UUID, a constant that never changes.
 It is stored in the flashlight computer memory itself, and does not change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In general, we'll wish to keep the cloud of flashlights relatively small,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\ll r_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a valid assumption.
 It seems like this could be a useful simplifying assumption, at some point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The flashlights are meant to be uniformly distributed, so that we can meaningful
ly talk about a Euclidean measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 describing the local density of the flashlights.
 We will want to track the time evolution of this measure, although this
 might prove to be a challenging task.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let the polar coordinates of a flashlight be denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\alpha\le\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\pi\le\beta\le\pi$
\end_inset

.
 These are the altitude and azimuth, respectively.
 The convention is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 is the zenith, pointing towards the black hole.
 The azimuth 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 must be specified with respect to the celestial meridian.
 It is aligned so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
 (That is, each flashlight will be located at some 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\ne0$
\end_inset

 and therefore at some generally non-zero 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 It is convenient to place the meridian 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0$
\end_inset

 at the same place where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

.) Let the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 be reserved for the third Euler angle, which will be needed to determine
 the flashlight polarization.
 It will be defined later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These angular coordinates are meant only to uniquely identify each flashlight.
 Again, they are a UUID assigned to each flashlight.
 This UUID number does not change over time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The orthonormal coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 for the lab frame (body frame) are related in the standard way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =R\sin\alpha\cos\beta\\
y & =R\sin\alpha\sin\beta\\
z & =R\cos\alpha
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Positive 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 points towards the black hole, it corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 Positive 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0$
\end_inset

.
 The coordinates are right-handed, so that positive 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\pi/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Initial flashlight positions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the above notation, let us then describe the geodesic of each flashlight,
 together with the lab frame center.
 Let each flashlight be denoted by a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is understood to be the UUID of the flashlight.
 We wish to relate the lab-frame coordinates to the Schwarzschild coordinate
 chart in the Schwarzschild spacetime manifold.
 Furthermore, we want to track each flashlight individually, as it falls.
 Thus, we solve the geodesic equation for radially infalling flashlights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x,y,z\right)$
\end_inset

 is located at the Schwarschild location 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,\theta,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 given by inverting the relations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =r\sin\theta\cos\phi\\
y & =r\sin\theta\sin\phi\\
z & =r\cos\theta-r_{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The distribution of the cloud is such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 The center of the cloud is at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y=z=0$
\end_inset

, and so at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Flashlight geodesics (in the Schwarzschild chart)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At later times, we wish to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r & =r\left(p,\tau\right)\\
\theta & =\theta\left(p,\tau\right)\\
\phi & =\phi\left(p,\tau\right)\\
t & =t\left(p,\tau\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so that for a given flashlight 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and a given proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, it is located at the above Schwarzschild coordinates.
 Each individual flashlight is meant to free-fall radially inwards.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Geodesic equations via Christoffel symbols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section attempts to brute-force our way through the geodesic equations.
 This is more or less always a mistake, as it is painful both to obtain
 the Christoffel symbols, and to then integrate the geodesics.
 A different reason that this is a mistake is that it almost always obscures
 the geometric properties of the system.
 However, for this section, we choose to make this mistake, mostly because
 Schwarschild should not be all that hard, and it also provides a good alternati
ve route.
 Even so, lets take some shortcuts, and copy what we need from existing
 texts, which is good enough for present purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume Wikipedia is correct (it wasn't, but I just now fixed it, after
 enduring some calculational pain), and work with the Wikipedia article
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Schwarzschild geodesics"
target "https://en.whttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwarzschild_geodesicsikipedia.org/wiki/Schwarzschild_geodesics"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This states
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\frac{d\phi}{d\tau}\\
0 & =\frac{d\theta}{d\tau}\\
0 & =\frac{d^{2}t}{d\tau^{2}}+\frac{1}{w}\frac{dw}{dr}\frac{dt}{d\tau}\frac{dr}{d\tau}\\
0 & =\frac{d^{2}r}{d\tau^{2}}-\frac{1}{v}\frac{dv}{dr}\left(\frac{dr}{d\tau}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2v}\frac{dw}{dr}\left(\frac{dt}{d\tau}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(r\right)=1-2m/r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(r\right)=1/w$
\end_inset

.
 I hand-verified the above.
 It's correct.
 The third equation corresponds to a constant of motion 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\left[\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\frac{dt}{d\tau}\right]=0
\]

\end_inset

which is given by the energy
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=m\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\frac{dt}{d\tau}
\]

\end_inset

At time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 and at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{0}\gg2m$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $dt/d\tau\approx1$
\end_inset

 because we are far away.
 This gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\approx m\left(1-\frac{2m}{r_{0}}\right)\approx m
\]

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t\left(p,\tau\right)=\frac{E}{m}\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}\frac{r\left(p,s\right)}{r\left(p,s\right)-2m}ds
\]

\end_inset

Yuck.
 Ugly.
 For the radial equation, I get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{d^{2}r}{d\tau^{2}}-\frac{m}{r^{2}}\frac{1}{\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)}\left[\left(\frac{dr}{d\tau}\right)^{2}-\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Rearranging, this gives the eqn
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{2}\frac{d^{2}r}{d\tau^{2}}\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)=m\left[\left(\frac{dr}{d\tau}\right)^{2}-\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right]
\]

\end_inset

which is sinfully ugly.
 Solutions can be brute-forced; these are given below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Geodesic equations via Lagrangian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section is mostly a recapitulation of the presentation provided in
 the course notes 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Radial Infall Lecture 31 Physics 411 Classical Mechanics II 14 November 2007 Reed College"
target "https://www.reed.edu/physics/courses/Physics411/html/411/page2/files/Lecture.31.pdf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Its slightly more verbose in some places, and more compact in others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian for a massive particle following a time-like trajectory is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}\dot{x}^{\mu}\dot{x}^{\nu}
\]

\end_inset

where the shorthand 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}^{\mu}=\frac{dx^{\mu}}{d\tau}
\]

\end_inset

is used.
 It's also handy to recall the Legendre transform.
 Defining the conjugate momentum as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\mu}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}^{\mu}}
\]

\end_inset

the Hamiltonian is then 
\begin_inset Formula $H=p_{\mu}\dot{x}^{\mu}-L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Schwarzschild chart, it is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{2}\left(\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\dot{t}^{2}-\frac{\dot{r}^{2}}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}-r^{2}\dot{\theta}^{2}-r^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

For radial infall, set 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}=\dot{\phi}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The Euler-Lagrange equations are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}^{\mu}}-\frac{\partial L}{\partial x^{\mu}}=0
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}=t$
\end_inset

 one obviously has 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial L/\partial t=0$
\end_inset

 and so one has a constant of motion:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{const}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{t}}
\]

\end_inset

Call this the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Working this out explicitly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{const}=\frac{E}{m}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{t}}=\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\dot{t}
\]

\end_inset

This is writen so that the constant is dimensionless, and the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 has the same units as the mass.
 This eqn is the same as the previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}=r$
\end_inset

, the radial equation is brute-forced:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=\frac{m}{r^{2}}\dot{t}^{2}+\frac{\dot{r}^{2}}{\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{2}}\frac{m}{r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

Plugging in for the energy,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=\frac{m}{r^{2}\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{2}}\left(\dot{r}^{2}+\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The momentum is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{r}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}=-\frac{\dot{r}}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}=-\frac{\ddot{r}}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}+\frac{\dot{r}^{2}}{\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{2}}\frac{2m}{r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}-\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=-\frac{\ddot{r}}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}+\frac{m}{r^{2}\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)^{2}}\left(\dot{r}^{2}-\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Rearranging, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{2}\ddot{r}\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)=m\left(\dot{r}^{2}-\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which is the same as the earlier eqn.
 So we got the same equation two different ways.
 Hurrah! I think it's correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Newtonian limit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can plug in for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{t}$
\end_inset

 in the Lagrangian to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{1-\frac{2m}{r}}\left(\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}-\dot{r}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Inserting this into the geodesic equation gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{2}\ddot{r}=-2mL
\]

\end_inset

This can be directly compared to the Newtonian limit.
 This would be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{r}=-\frac{Gm}{r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 was inserted explicitly, just to jog the memory.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1$
\end_inset

 in our units.
 From this, one may conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1/2$
\end_inset

 for massive particles falling in the radial direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There's a second case, obtained by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}=\pm\frac{E}{m}
\]

\end_inset

solves the geodesic equation, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging through, one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since the Lagrangian was explicitly constructed from the metric, one concludes
 that these are null geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Timelike radial geodesics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A solution for the radial geodesic equation can be found with the Ansatz
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{r}\ddot{r}= & \frac{1}{2}\frac{d}{d\tau}\dot{r}^{2}\\
= & -\frac{m\dot{r}}{r^{2}}\\
= & \frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{m}{r}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Integrating this gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{r}^{2}=\frac{2m}{r}+A
\]

\end_inset

with a constant of integration 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The simplest way to solve this is to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

 and then invert, rather than trying to get to 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 directly.
 This is done by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\tau}{dr}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{r}{2m+Ar}}
\]

\end_inset

For now, set 
\begin_inset Formula $A=0$
\end_inset

; the case for 
\begin_inset Formula $A\ne0$
\end_inset

 is considered later.
 Integrating this directly gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\tau\left(r\right)=\tau_{0}\pm\frac{2}{3}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2m}}\left(r^{3/2}-r_{0}^{3/2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}=r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the initial position of flashlight 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 at initial time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The infalling geodesic corresponds to the choice of the minus sign, so
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $r<r_{0}$
\end_inset

 results in increasing proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau>\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Inverting this gives the rather busy expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\left(\tau\right)=\left[r_{0}^{3/2}-\frac{3\sqrt{2m}}{2}\left(\tau-\tau_{0}\right)\right]^{2/3}
\]

\end_inset

Curiously, this expression is not singular at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=2m$
\end_inset

.
 However, the integral providing the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 does exhibit a pole at that point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the moment, there's no need for an equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 and being lazy, it's omitted.
 The Reed College notes, op.
 cit.
 provide this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Null radially geodesics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides the above, one can also go back to the earlier form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{2}\ddot{r}\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)=m\left(\dot{r}^{2}-\frac{E^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}=\pm E/m=\mbox{const.}$
\end_inset

 appears to be a valid solution.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}=0$
\end_inset

 and both the left and right hand sides vanish.
 This provides the solution for null geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Treating this as a valid solution for the exterior, then integration gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\left(p,\tau\right)=r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)-\frac{E}{m}\left(\tau-\tau_{0}\right)
\]

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
t\left(p,\tau\right)= & \frac{E}{m}\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}\frac{r\left(p,s\right)}{r\left(p,s\right)-2m}ds\\
= & \frac{E}{m}\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}\frac{r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)-\frac{E}{m}\left(s-\tau_{0}\right)}{r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)-\frac{E}{m}\left(s-\tau_{0}\right)-2m}ds\\
= & \left(r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)+\frac{E\tau_{0}}{m}\right)\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}\frac{ds}{K-s}-\frac{E}{m}\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}\frac{sds}{K-s}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K=\frac{m}{E}r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)+\tau_{0}-\frac{2m^{2}}{E}
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s-K=u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ds=du$
\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
t\left(p,\tau\right)= & -\left(r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)+\frac{E\tau_{0}}{m}\right)\int_{\tau_{0}-K}^{\tau-K}\frac{du}{u}-\frac{E}{m}\int_{\tau_{0}}^{\tau}\frac{sds}{K-s}\\
= & -\left(r\left(p,\tau_{0}\right)+\frac{E\tau_{0}}{m}\right)\int_{\tau_{0}-K}^{\tau-K}\frac{du}{u}+\frac{E}{m}K\int_{\tau_{0}-K}^{\tau-K}\frac{du}{u}+\frac{E}{m}\int_{\tau_{0}-K}^{\tau-K}du\\
= & -\frac{2m^{2}}{E}\log\frac{\tau-K}{\tau_{0}-K}+\frac{E}{m}\left(\tau-\tau_{0}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

