\begin_layout Standard
First, the Lemaître frame for Schwarszchild.
 This frame is for a freely-falling, non-spinning point particle.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\vec{f}_{0} & =\partial_{T}-\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}\partial_{r}\\
\vec{f}_{1} & =\partial_{r}\\
\vec{f}_{2} & =\frac{1}{r}\partial_{\theta}\\
\vec{f}_{3} & =\frac{1}{r\sin\theta}\partial_{\phi}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ds^{2}=dT^{2}-\left(dr+\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}dT\right)^{2}-r^{2}\left(d\theta^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\,d\phi^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Note that for constant 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 (by abuse of notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $dT=0$
\end_inset

) the spatial part of the metric is the flat-space metric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
